description.plain:
DeShaun Dupree Holton (a.k.a. Proof) was an American rapper from Detroit, Michigan. He was born on October 2, 1973 to a single mother. His father, a music producer named McKinley Jackson, left Holton and his mother to pursue a career in music.

Proof rose to prominence in the hip-hop scene as part of the rap-group D12. He was good friends with fellow D12 member, Eminem, and was considered his hype man. In 2001, D12 released Devil’s Night, their most famous album. He also played Lil Tic in the film 8 Mile.

He has also done solo work and collaborated with artists like 50 Cent and Method Man.

Sadly, he was shot and killed in a Detroit nightclub on April 11, 2006. According to local police, he was shot after an altercation had occurred, but witnesses tell different accounts of what actually happened that night.

description.plain:
This is a diss track by Proof aka Big Proof (Deshaun Holton), hype man to Eminem and member of the rap group D12, against Benzino (Raymond Scott), part of the ongoing beef between Benzino and Eminem and his crew. Benzino was the co-owner, with Dave Mays, of The Source Magazine, which had been known as “the Bible” of hip hop before Benzino began using it to promote his own rap group, Made Men.  In this track, Proof and his featured artist, D12’s Swifty McVay, respond to Benzino’s diss tracks accusing D12 of being “house [blacks]”,  and tracks threatening Eminem, his manager, his daughter Hailie, and acts signed to Eminem’s label Shady Records, such as D12 and 50 Cent. They also respond to articles in The Source  accusing Eminem of racism and Interscope Records (parent company of Shady Records) of using Eminem to usurp the hip hop game for white artists and push black hip hop artists out.  This beef was a dangerous one and  resulted in Proof getting jumped in Miami.  Benzino took credit for the attack in his diss track “Built for This.”

D12 with Proof (in yellow), Eminem (bottom middle) and Swifty McVay (bottom right)
